- In the last video, we worked through

00:00:02.319 --> 00:00:03.966
essentially the probability distribution

00:00:03.966 --> 00:00:06.683
for this random variable defined as

00:00:06.683 --> 00:00:08.378
the number of free throws you make

00:00:08.378 --> 00:00:10.177
when taking size free throws,

00:00:10.177 --> 00:00:12.777
assuming you have a 70
percent free throw percentage,

00:00:12.777 --> 00:00:15.041
and I suggested, hey, why
don't you visualize this?

00:00:15.041 --> 00:00:18.106
Draw the graph of this
probability distribution,

00:00:18.106 --> 00:00:20.405
this binomial probability distribution.

00:00:20.405 --> 00:00:21.519
And when I thought about it, I said,

00:00:21.519 --> 00:00:23.557
well, I too would enjoy graphing it,

00:00:23.557 --> 00:00:24.708
and we might as well do it together,

00:00:24.708 --> 00:00:26.541
because whenever you graph these things

00:00:26.541 --> 00:00:27.563
it makes it very visual,

00:00:27.563 --> 00:00:31.765
and kind of the shape of a
binomial distribution like this.

00:00:31.765 --> 00:00:33.614
So let's do that.

00:00:33.614 --> 00:00:37.132
So let me maybe move over
to the right a little bit,

00:00:37.132 --> 00:00:38.177
I really just need to
be able to keep track

00:00:38.177 --> 00:00:42.036
of these things right over here.

00:00:42.036 --> 00:00:45.421
Let me draw some lines.

00:00:45.605 --> 00:00:49.983
If I were to just draw one line there,

00:00:49.983 --> 00:00:53.919
and then another line here,

00:00:53.919 --> 00:00:57.064
and then we have the
different percentages.

00:00:57.064 --> 00:00:58.539
So let's do that.

00:00:58.539 --> 00:01:02.359
See, the highest one is
a little over 32 percent.

00:01:02.359 --> 00:01:05.842
So maybe we'll go as
high as 40 percent here.

00:01:05.842 --> 00:01:10.842
40 percent, and then
this would be 20 percent.

00:01:12.077 --> 00:01:15.177
20, that looks about half way, 20 percent.

00:01:15.177 --> 00:01:19.680
This would be 10 percent.

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.918
And this would be 30 percent.

00:01:23.918 --> 00:01:27.075
And then in this axis, let's
do the different values

00:01:27.075 --> 00:01:29.583
that the random variable could take on.

00:01:29.583 --> 00:01:33.090
So the random variable taking on

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:35.741
the value zero.

00:01:35.741 --> 00:01:40.280
The random variable
taking on the value one.

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:45.280
Zero, one, the random
variable taking on two.

00:01:46.604 --> 00:01:49.621
Two, we're almost there.

00:01:49.621 --> 00:01:54.621
Let's see, three, and then four.

00:01:55.170 --> 00:01:59.687
Four, and then five.

00:01:59.687 --> 00:02:02.729
Five, and then finally six.

00:02:02.729 --> 00:02:05.005
Take x equals six.

00:02:05.005 --> 00:02:07.626
And then six, and now let's
just graph all of these.

00:02:07.626 --> 00:02:10.712
So this first one, zero point one percent,

00:02:10.712 --> 00:02:11.851
well, that's barely going to register

00:02:11.851 --> 00:02:13.093
